Introduction -- tEyes Wide Open … -- t8. Getting Beyond “It Changed My Life”: Assessment of Out There Transformation -- t9:14 AM: Saturday, 14 May 2016 -- t“The World Moves Through Us” … -- t9. Assessing Learning “Out There”: Four Key Challenges and Opportunities -- tEmbracing Complexities … -- t10. Transformation in the Field: Short-Term Study Abroad and the Pursuit of Changes -- tEducation Can Be Empowering … -- tConcluding Remarks -- tAppendix: Field School Briefings -- tContributors and Editors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUniversities across North America and beyond are experiencing growing demand for off-campus, experiential learning. Exploring the foundations of what it means to learn "out there," Out There Learning is an informed, critical investigation of the pedagogical philosophies and practices involved in short-term, off-campus programs or field courses. Bringing together contributors’ individual research and experience teaching or administering off-campus study programs, Out There Learning examines and challenges common assumptions about pedagogy, place, and personal transformation, while also providing experience-based insights and advice for getting the most out of faculty-led field courses. Divided into three sections that investigate aspects of pedagogy, ethics of place, and course and program assessment, this collection offers "voices from the field" highlighting the experiences of faculty members, students, teaching assistants, and community members engaged in every aspect of an off-campus study programs. Several chapters examine study programs in the traditional territories of Indigenous communities and in the Global South. Containing an appendix highlighting some examples of off-campus study programs, Out There Learning offers new pathways for faculty, staff, and college and university administrators interested in enriching the experience of non-traditional avenues of study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCommunity and college. 0aService learning. 0aUniversity extension. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh  aEducation.  afield course.  afield school.  ageography.  aoff-campus study.  apedagogy.  aplace.1 aBorrows, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchan, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastleden, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurran, Deborah Louise, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCurran, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaley, Kiley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElwood, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFormby, Liah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlass, Michael R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalvorsen, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, Megan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Aisling, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKerr, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLax, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMckinney, Kacy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyer-Lee, Elaine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMusisi, Nakanyike B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOwens, Cameron , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela